context: By the <a0_0><a0_1><b5_0>6th century<b5_0/><a0_1/><a0_0/>, the Rhine was within the borders of Francia. In the 9th, it formed part of the border between Middle and Western Francia, but in the <a1_0><a1_1><a1_2><b6_0>10th century<b6_0/><a1_2/><a1_1/><a1_0/>, it was fully within the Holy Roman Empire, flowing through Swabia, Franconia and <a2_0><a2_1><a2_2>Lower Lorraine<a2_2/><a2_1/><a2_0/>. The mouths of the Rhine, in the county of Holland, fell to the Burgundian Netherlands in the <b7_0>15th century<b7_0/>; Holland remained contentious territory throughout the European wars of religion and the eventual collapse of the Holy Roman Empire, when the length of the Rhine fell to the First French Empire and its client states. The Alsace on the left banks of the Upper Rhine was sold to Burgundy by <a3_0><a3_1><a3_2>Archduke Sigismund<a3_0/> of Austria<a3_2/><a3_1/> in <a4_0><a4_1><a4_2><b8_0>1469<b8_0/><a4_2/><a4_1/><a4_0/> and eventually fell to France in the <b9_0>Thirty Years' War<b9_0/>. The numerous historic castles in Rhineland-Palatinate attest to the importance of the river as a commercial route.
